WARSAW &ndash; Polish KGHM, one of the world&#39;s biggest copper producers, reported on Friday a 147% rise in its first quarter consolidated net profit boosted by metal prices and weaker zloty. The state-run miner posted a consolidated net profit of 398-million zlotys ($103.81-million) compared to 161-million zlotys the company reported a year ago. At a stand-alone level, on which KGHM&#39;s dividends are based and which reflects the company&#39;s operations in Poland, the miner booked a net profit of 805-million zlotys compared with 370-million zlotys a year earlier.